; specs/grammar/identifiers.abnf
; RFC-0001 — Identifiers and Identity (the did:mf DID Method Specification)
; Status: Draft. This grammar is NOT normative until the RFC is Ratified
; (see specs/README.md). Grounding behaviour on a Draft is an error.
;
; This file is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH for the identifier terminals that
; RFC-0002 (Subject Namespace) and RFC-0003 (Envelope) reference. Terminal
; alphabets are defined ONCE here; sibling RFCs cite them, never redefine
; them (grammar/README.md rule 5).
;
; Core rules ALPHA, DIGIT are imported from RFC 5234 Appendix B.

; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; 1. Base identifier terminals.
;    These are BOTH NATS subject segments AND the substrings a DID is minted
;    from. Each is a faithful transcription of a live regex; the source is
;    cited so that after generation the arrow reverses — the regex becomes
;    the artifact and THIS becomes its source.
; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

; lower — the lowercase-letter alphabet every metafactory identifier starts
; with.
lower           = %x61-7A                        ; a-z

; principal-id — a principal slug (the owner of a stack; second token of a
; namespaced NATS subject). Transcribes PRINCIPAL_RE,
; myelin src/patterns.ts:35   /^[a-z][a-z0-9-]{0,62}[a-z0-9]$/
; 2–64 chars; first char a letter; final char alphanumeric; interior "-"
; PERMITTED, INCLUDING two or more consecutive "-" (unlike a DID
; method-specific-id, which forbids "--"). A trailing "-" is FORBIDDEN.
principal-id    = lower *62( lower / DIGIT / "-" ) ( lower / DIGIT )

; stack-slug — the per-deployment stack segment. Transcribes
; STACK_SEGMENT_REGEX, myelin src/segment-validators.ts:27
;   /^[a-z][a-z0-9-]{0,62}$/
; 1–63 chars; first char a letter; a TRAILING "-" IS PERMITTED. This DIVERGES
; from principal-id (which forbids a trailing "-") and from CAPABILITY_TAG_RE
; (which forbids both trailing and consecutive "-"). The divergence is a
; finding recorded in the RFC Security Considerations, NOT a design.
stack-slug      = lower *62( lower / DIGIT / "-" )

; stack-id — the {principal}/{stack} pair rendered with a literal "/".
; The "/" is REQUIRED. A bare principal with no "/" is a FAULT and MUST NOT
; be fabricated into a "default" stack (root cause of cortex#1812).
stack-id        = principal-id "/" stack-slug

; agent-id / service-id / hub-id — the names of the agent-, service-, and
; hub-class identities (IdentityType, myelin src/identity/types.ts:6). NO
; per-class alphabet exists anywhere in the source: the ONLY constraint on
; each of them is the DID method-specific-id alphabet. They are defined here
; as aliases to make that absence explicit. That FIVE classes (agent,
; service, hub, principal, stack) share ONE undifferentiated alphabet is the
; central finding of this RFC (see Security Considerations §"Flat-namespace
; class collision"), and is the subject of the OPEN DECISION on
; method-specific-id below.
agent-id        = did-msi-deployed
service-id      = did-msi-deployed
hub-id          = did-msi-deployed

; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; 2. The did:mf Decentralized Identifier.
; ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

; did — a metafactory DID (W3C DID Core §3.1 conforming shape).
did             = did-prefix method-specific-id
did-prefix      = %x64.69.64.3A.6D.66.3A         ; "did:mf:" (case-sensitive)

; method-specific-id — *** OPEN DECISION — Andreas + JC —
; blocked on the-metafactory/cortex#1880. ***
;
; This rule is a TBD PLACEHOLDER. The canonical, class-unambiguous grammar
; CANNOT be written until cortex#1880 selects among the candidate encodings
; (RFC §6.2). Presented, NOT chosen:
;
;   Candidate A  forbid-hyphen       ; forbid "-" in the principal so the
;                                    ; {principal}-{stack} join is unambiguous.
;                                    ; SHOWN INSUFFICIENT: agent- and
;                                    ; service-class ids are themselves
;                                    ; hyphenated and share the flat namespace
;                                    ; (e.g. did:mf:signal-tap), and deployed
;                                    ; principals already contain hyphens.
;   Candidate B  new-separator       ; reserve a delimiter that is illegal
;                                    ; inside EVERY base id alphabet.
;   Candidate C  class-explicit "."  ; carry class/structure with ".". "." is
;                                    ; ACCEPTED by the deployed grammar and
;                                    ; FORBIDDEN in every base id alphabet
;                                    ; ([a-z0-9-] only), so it is unambiguous,
;                                    ; needs NO schema change, and is
;                                    ; W3C-conformant.
;   Candidate D  keep-runtime-guard  ; status quo — leave the grammar as-is;
;                                    ; the class collision stays held shut by
;                                    ; a runtime check (a finding, not a fix).
;
method-specific-id = did-msi-deployed
                ; ^ PLACEHOLDER binding. Until cortex#1880 resolves, the
                ;   deployed grammar below is what EVERY implementation
                ;   actually accepts today. It is transcribed for fidelity,
                ;   NOT endorsed as the target: it admits the class collisions
                ;   and degenerate forms documented in the RFC.

; did-msi-deployed — the CURRENTLY-DEPLOYED method-specific-id. Faithful
; transcription of DID_RE, myelin src/identity/types.ts:1
;   /^did:mf:[a-z](?:[a-z0-9._]|-(?!-))+$/
; (the leading "did:mf:" and the ^…$ anchors are supplied by `did`).
; Semantics: first char a letter; total length >= 2; "." and "_" permitted
; anywhere after the first char, INCLUDING consecutively; a single "-"
; permitted wherever it is NOT immediately followed by another "-" (the
; negative lookahead -(?!-)); NO upper length bound; a trailing "-", ".", or
; "_" is permitted. The only sequence it forbids is "--".
did-msi-deployed = lower ( 1*msi-run [ "-" ] / "-" )
msi-run          = 1*msi-symbol / "-" 1*msi-symbol
msi-symbol       = lower / DIGIT / "." / "_"
